# Part 1 - Database Architecture

## Purpose

The database is a strategic business asset.

Databases must support

- Domain-Driven Design
- Microservices
- Event-Driven Architecture
- AI
- Multi-Tenancy
- Plugin Architecture
- Scalability
- Reliability
- Long-term evolution

Databases must never dictate architecture.

Business architecture determines database architecture.

---

## Database Philosophy

Business Capability

↓

Bounded Context

↓

Microservice

↓

Aggregate

↓

Database Schema

↓

Tables

Business owns data.

Applications access data.

Services never own another service's data.

---

## Database Ownership

Each database belongs to exactly one microservice.

Each schema belongs to exactly one bounded context.

Each table belongs to exactly one aggregate.

Each aggregate belongs to exactly one service.

Ownership is never shared.

---

## Database Per Service

Every microservice owns its own database schema.

Example

Identity Service

↓

identity_schema

Lead Service

↓

lead_schema

Customer Service

↓

customer_schema

Conversation Service

↓

conversation_schema

Workflow Service

↓

workflow_schema

Notification Service

↓

notification_schema

Billing Service

↓

billing_schema

AI Service

↓

ai_schema

Search Service

↓

search_schema

Media Service

↓

media_schema

Platform Service

↓

platform_schema

Plugins own their own schemas.

---

## Shared Database Policy

Microservices never

Read another service's tables.

Write another service's tables.

Join another service's tables.

Modify another service's schema.

Communication occurs through

REST

Events

Read Models

Never through database access.

---

## Aggregate Ownership

Every Aggregate owns

Its tables

Its relationships

Its constraints

Its business invariants

Only the owning microservice may modify aggregate data.

---

## Schema Ownership

Every schema has

Business Owner

Technical Owner

Bounded Context

Owning Microservice

No shared schema ownership is permitted.

---

