## Part 2 - Database Design Standards

## Database Design Philosophy

Database design must support

- Business correctness
- Scalability
- Performance
- Maintainability
- Evolution
- Tenant isolation

Database schema follows the Domain Model.

Never design databases from UI screens.

Never design databases from REST APIs.

---

## Naming Standards

Use

snake_case

Examples

lead

lead_status

customer_address

conversation_message

workflow_execution

Never use

LeadTable

tbl_lead

LEAD_MASTER

customerDetails

Database naming must remain consistent.

---

## Table Naming

Tables represent Aggregates or Aggregate Components.

Examples

lead

customer

appointment

conversation

workflow_execution

notification

Never create

generic_data

master_table

temp_table

common_table

Table names must describe business meaning.

---

## Column Naming

Use

snake_case

Examples

tenant_id

organization_id

lead_id

created_at

updated_at

created_by

updated_by

deleted_at

version

Avoid abbreviations.

Column names must be self-explanatory.

---

## Primary Keys

Every table uses

UUID

Example

id UUID PRIMARY KEY

Never use auto-increment IDs for distributed services.

UUIDs support

Microservices

Offline processing

Event-driven architecture

Data migration

---

## Foreign Keys

Allowed

Within the same bounded context.

Forbidden

Across microservices.

Never reference another service's tables.

Cross-service relationships are maintained through

REST

Events

Identifiers

---

## Aggregate Boundaries

Relationships remain inside the Aggregate.

Never create cross-aggregate write dependencies.

Aggregate consistency belongs to the owning service.

---

## Audit Columns

Every business table contains

id

tenant_id

organization_id

created_at

created_by

updated_at

updated_by

version

Optional

deleted_at

deleted_by

Audit information is mandatory.

---

## Optimistic Locking

Every mutable aggregate includes

version

Optimistic locking prevents lost updates.

Never rely solely on last-write-wins.

---

## Soft Delete

Use

deleted_at

deleted_by

Never permanently remove business records unless required by business policy.

Hard deletes require explicit approval.

---

## Constraints

Use database constraints for

Primary Keys

Foreign Keys (within the service)

Unique Constraints

Check Constraints

Not Null Constraints

Business invariants remain in the Domain Model.

---

## Unique Constraints

Examples

email

tenant_id + external_reference

tenant_id + code

tenant_id + phone_number

Always include tenant context where uniqueness is tenant-specific.

---

## Index Strategy

Indexes must support

Primary Keys

Foreign Keys

Tenant filtering

Search predicates

Ordering

Frequently queried columns

Avoid unnecessary indexes.

Every index has a maintenance cost.

---

## Composite Indexes

Examples

tenant_id + status

tenant_id + created_at

tenant_id + customer_id

tenant_id + updated_at

Composite indexes should match common query patterns.

---

## JSONB Usage

Use JSONB only for

Dynamic configuration

Plugin configuration

Metadata

AI model responses

Provider-specific payloads

Never store core business entities in JSONB.

---

## Enum Strategy

Prefer

Reference tables

or

Application enums

Avoid database enums when values evolve frequently.

Choose the approach that best supports future changes.

---

## Flyway

Every schema change requires

Versioned migration

Descriptive migration name

Rollback strategy where practical

Never modify an applied migration.

Create a new migration instead.

---

## Migration Rules

Allowed

Add tables

Add nullable columns

Add indexes

Add optional fields

Forbidden

Modify historical migrations

Drop columns without migration planning

Rename columns directly in production

Breaking changes require staged migrations.

---

## Default Values

Database defaults are allowed only for

created_at

updated_at

version

Boolean flags where appropriate

Avoid business defaults inside the database.

Business defaults belong in the application.

---

## Transactions

Transactions remain

Inside one microservice.

Never attempt distributed database transactions.

Cross-service consistency uses

Events

Saga

Workflow

---

## Read Optimization

Optimize reads using

Indexes

Read models

Caching

Search projections

Never denormalize transactional data without a documented reason.

---

## Write Optimization

Prioritize

Correctness

Consistency

Idempotency

Business invariants

Over premature optimization.

---

## Data Integrity

Database guarantees

Structural integrity

Domain guarantees

Business integrity

Application Services and Aggregates enforce business rules.

---

## Performance

Review

Slow queries

Missing indexes

Large tables

Query plans

Lock contention

Deadlocks

Performance must be monitored continuously.

---

## Repository Intelligence

Before creating

Table

Column

Index

Constraint

Migration

The agent must search the repository.

Questions

Does this table already exist?

Does this aggregate already own the data?

Can the existing schema evolve?

Is a migration sufficient?

Avoid duplicate database structures.

---

## Review Checklist

Before implementing verify

✓ Naming follows standards

✓ UUID primary key

✓ Tenant columns included

✓ Audit columns included

✓ Optimistic locking included

✓ Appropriate constraints defined

